<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-019-010  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 019 010.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Software  Jan 1990 v7 n1 p90(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Reverse-engineering someone else's software: is it legal?andO;(intellectual-property law)(includes related articles on case law,legal issues in other contexts)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Samuelson, Pamela.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The issue of whether reverse-engineering with today'ssophisticated software-analysis tools violatesintellectual-property laws is widely debated among both technicaland legal professionals.andP;  Some lawyers argue thatreverse-engineering copyrighted software is illegal because itinvolves unauthorized copying of programs and is amisappropriation of trade secrets.andP;  This 'strict constructionist'view interprets copyright statutes narrowly and notes that thesoftware industry is vulnerable to the theft of valuable andcostly innovations.andP;  A more pragmatic view, based on the 'fairuse' doctrine, holds that reverse engineering is legal because anycopying of the code that takes place is incidental and becauseother engineering disciplines accept reverse-engineering as alegal way to take trade secrets.andP;  Engineers should avoid copyingprotected expressions or publishing trade secrets.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Reverse EngineeringLegal IssuesIntellectual PropertyPatentCopyrightGuidelines.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>